posts.cooked: Where should my team buy rack gears for FRC ? We’re planning on using them for a lift, but we can’t find good gears anywhere. Is it easier to just make them on the CNC?

posts.name: Jared Van Horn
posts.cooked:
These gear racks are great for powered linear motion! This will give you the positional control that pneumatics can't. Comes in 10DP & 20DP options Made from 6061-T6 Aluminum #10-32 Clearance Holes Both come in 35.5" lengths which allows for...

Price: USD 34.99
Are those strong enough for high stress vertical movement?

posts.name: Jared Van Horn
posts.cooked: I have personally never used them. It depends on what you’re using them for. I imagine you could have multiple stacked on top of each other to add to the strength but if you’re doing something super intense like lifting your whole robot I have doubts they’d hold.
Basically we’re using them as a cheap substitute for a cascade lift, because we’re a smaller team and brand new, we’re not the wealthiest currently

posts.name: Patrick
posts.cooked:
McMaster has racks in a variety of sizes that would be much stronger than the WCP ones, but they’re going to be much harder to mount in most situations.

In general racks are going to be a heavier and more difficult to execute way to achieve linear motion than belts and chains.

posts.name: Alex Richards
posts.cooked:
We’ve used McMaster steel gear rack in the past successfully. We drilled a lot of shallow 8-32 holes in the back to bolt it directly to a tube.

posts.name: 829 The Digital Goats Official Curmudgeon.
posts.cooked: We have used McMaster rack gears several times including last year. We have mounted through the face and the sides.

posts.name: Aidan McMaster
posts.cooked:
Probably an easier and more robust solution for you:

if you have a sprocket at the top and the bottom of your lift tower, you can run a chain between them and pin the chain to the first stage. Then you just have to spin the sprocket, and the stage will move up and down. The next cascaded stage can be done with cable

posts.name: Eric Bergquist
posts.cooked:
To get a rough idea of whether the WCP gear racks are strong enough, you can divide the shear strength of 6061-T6 aluminum by the cross-sectional area of one tooth at the pitch depth (roughly halfway up the tooth). According to Matweb , the shear strength of 6061-T6 is 30,000psi (pounds per square inch). The area for the 10DP gear rack (which I would recommend over 20DP) is 0.157"x0.125", or 0.0196 square inches. This means that the failure strength of one tooth at the pitch line is 588 pounds. Assuming that you have a rack on either side of your elevator, that combines to 1177 pounds at failure, which I would call a good factor of safety even for dynamic loading.

Now, if you need a longer gear rack than 35.5", then you would need to add cost and buy 4 gear racks, but this price seems to still be in line with the price of McMaster 20dp options.
